{"title_page": "Matt Hancock", "text_new": "{{about|the British politician|the character from the soap opera ''Neighbours''|Matt Hancock (Neighbours)}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Matt Hancock\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Matt Hancock MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start1 = 9 July 2018\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Jeremy Hunt]]\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 8 January 2018\n| term_end2 = 9 July 2018\n| predecessor2 = [[Karen Bradley]]\n| successor2 = [[Jeremy Wright]]\n| office3 = [[Minister for Culture, Communications and Creative Industries|Minister of State for Digital and Culture]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start3 = 15 July 2016\n| term_end3 = 8 January 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Ed Vaizey]]\n| successor3 = [[Margot James]]\n| office4 = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]]<br />[[Paymaster General]]\n| primeminister4 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start4 = 11 May 2015\n| term_end4 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor4 = [[Francis Maude]]\n| successor4 = [[Ben Gummer]]\n| office5 = [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Business and Enterprise]]\n| primeminister5 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start5 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end5 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor5 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor5 = [[Anna Soubry]]\n| office6 = [[Minister of State at the Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]\n| primeminister6 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start6 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end6 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor6 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor6 = [[Andrea Leadsom]]\n| office7 = [[Minister for Portsmouth|Minister of State for Portsmouth]]\n| primeminister7 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start7 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end7 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor7 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor7 = [[Mark Francois]]\n| office8 = [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Skills and Enterprise]]\n| primeminister8 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start8 = 8 September 2013\n| term_end8 = 15 July 2014\n| predecessor8 = [[John Hayes (British politician)|John Hayes]]\n| successor8 = [[Nick Boles]]\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]]\n| term_start9 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end9 = \n| predecessor9 = [[Richard Spring, Baron Risby|Richard Spring]]\n| successor9 = \n| majority9 = 23,194 (45.1%)\n| birth_name = Matthew John David Hancock\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|10|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Chester]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education = [[The King's School, Chester]]\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of Oxford]]\n* [[University of Cambridge]]\n}}\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{married|Martha Hoyer Millar|2006}}\n| children = 3\n| website = {{URL|www.matt-hancock.com}}\n| caption = Hancock in 2020\n}}\n'''Matthew John David Hancock''' (born 2 October 1978) is a  British politician serving as [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], since 2018. A member of the Clown Party, he has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]]. \n\nHancock was born in [[Cheshire]], where his family runs a software business. Hancock studied for a BA in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] (PPE) at [[Exeter College, Oxford]], and an MPhil in Economics at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], as a postgraduate student. He was an economist at the Bank of England before serving as a senior economic advisor (and later Chief of Staff) to [[George Osborne]].\n\nHancock served in a number of middle-ranking ministerial positions from September 2013 under both [[David Cameron]] and [[Theresa May]]. He was promoted to the Cabinet in the [[2018 British cabinet reshuffle|January 2018 cabinet reshuffle]] when he was appointed [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-42602570|title=Cabinet reshuffle: Greening quits government|publisher=BBC News|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> On 9 July 2018, after the promotion of [[Jeremy Hunt]] to Foreign Secretary, Hancock was named [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/matt-hancock-health-secretary-jeremy-hunt-app-theresa-may-foreign-secretary-boris-johnson-a8439506.html|title=Matt Hancock replaces Jeremy Hunt as health secretary|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> On 25 May 2019, Hancock announced his intention to stand in the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election]]. He withdrew from the race on 14 June shortly after the first ballot after finding  himself out of his depth.         \n\n==Early life and career==\nMatthew John David Hancock was born on 2 October 1978 in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], to Michael Hancock and Shirley Hills (now Carter).<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-251113|title=Hancock, Rt Hon. Matthew (John David)|publisher=UK Who's Who|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\nHancock attended Farndon County Primary School, in [[Farndon, Cheshire|Farndon]], Cheshire, and the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[King's School, Chester|King's School]], Chester. He later studied computing at the further education college, [[West Cheshire College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://feweek.co.uk/2014/04/24/with-two-offices-across-two-government-departments-two-secretaries-of-state-as-bosses-and-one-of-the-broadest-ministerial-briefs-around-life-is-hectic-for-matthew-hancock/|publisher=FE Week|date=24 April 2014|accessdate=18 October 2019|title=Matthew Hancock MP, skills minister|last=Whittaker|first=Freddie}}</ref><ref name=King>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingschester.co.uk/news/alumni-news/cabinet-role-mp-matt-hancock/|title=Cabinet role for MP Matt Hancock|publisher=King's School Chester|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> He studied at [[Exeter College, Oxford]], and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#First class honours|first]] in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]], and went on to [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], to earn an [[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]] degree in Economics.<ref name=King/><ref name=\"FTYoungMinister\">{{cite news |title=Young minister has the skills to climb to the top in Westminster |url=https://www.ft.com/content/027bd85e-0290-11e4-a68d-00144feab7de |accessdate=10 July 2018 |work=Financial Times}}</ref> Hancock became a member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/matthew-hancock/84378|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808232448/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/matthew-hancock/84378|archivedate=2012-08-08|title=Matthew Hancock|website=www.parliament.uk |date=8 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter university, Hancock briefly worked for his family's [[computer software]] company, before moving to London to work as an economist at the [[Bank of England]], specialising in the [[housing market]]. In 2005, he became an economic adviser to the [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[George Osborne]], later becoming Osborne's chief of staff.<ref name=\"FTYoungMinister\"/><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/voters-don-t-want-extremes-they-want-the-centre-cn9lbhqnz|title=Matt Hancock interview: 'Voters want the centre, not the extremes'|date=4 May 2019|last1=Thomson|first1=Alice|last2=Sylvester|first2=Rachel|work=The Times|accessdate=18 October 2019}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nHancock was selected as the Conservative candidate for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]] in January 2010. He narrowly won the contest, defeating [[Natalie Elphicke]] (solicitor and wife of politician [[Charlie Elphicke]]), by 88 votes to 81 in the final ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/highlights/2018/05/profile-matt-hancock-the-osborne-acolyte-who-managed-to-survive-and-prosper.html|publisher=Conservative Home|title=Profile: Matt Hancock, the Osborne acolyte who managed to survive and prosper|last=Gimson|first=Andrew|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHancock was elected as the Member of Parliament for West Suffolk at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] with 24,312 votes, 13,050 votes ahead of [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate Belinda Brooks-Gordon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/f10.stm |title=Election 2010: Constituency: Suffolk West |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> In June, Hancock was elected to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|select committee]] responsible for overseeing government expenditures to ensure they are effective and honest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/parliament/2010/06/members-of-the-2010-intake-dominate-the-conservative-membership-of-select-committees.html |title=Members of the 2010 intake dominate the Conservative membership of Select Committees Tory MPs |work=[[Conservative Home]] |date=24 June 2010 |accessdate=8 April 2015 |archivedate=27 June 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100627030054/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/parliament/2010/06/members-of-the-2010-intake-dominate-the-conservative-membership-of-select-committees.html }}</ref> He served on this committee until November 2012. Hancock has also served on the [[Standards and Privileges Committee]] between October 2010 and December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/matt-hancock/4070|title=Rt Hon Matt Hancock|accessdate=9 November 2019|publisher=parliament.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, he was accused of dishonesty by ''[[Daybreak (2010 TV programme)|Daybreak]]'' presenter [[Matt Barbet]] after claiming he had been excluded from a discussion about apprentices after turning up \"just 30 seconds late\".<ref name=\"HHH\">{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9795367/Hancocks-half-hour-Tory-minister-accused-of-dishonesty-about-missed-TV-appearance.html |title=Hancock's half-hour: Tory minister accused of 'dishonesty' about missed TV appearance |author=Peter Dominiczak |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> Barbet said Hancock knew he was \"much more than a minute late\" and he should have arrived half an hour beforehand to prepare for the interview. An activist who was due to appear with Hancock expressed surprise that \"a minister whose Government berates 'shirkers' couldn't be bothered to get out of bed to defend his own policy\".<ref name=\"HHH\"/>\n\n===Junior ministerial roles===\nIn October 2013, Hancock joined the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] as the Minister of State for Skills & Enterprise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityam.com/cabinet-reshuffle-who-matt-hancock-meet-david-cameron-s-new-minister-business-enterprise/|publisher=City A.M.|accessdate=9 November 2019|date=15 July 2014|title=Who is Matt Hancock? Meet David Cameron's new business minister}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 July 2014, Hancock was appointed to the position of Minister of State for Business and Enterprise.  He also took on additional responsibilities as the Minister of State for Portsmouth. On 27 July he announced protection from [[fracking]] for [[National parks of England and Wales|National Parks]]<ref name=\"pete\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fracking/10994412/National-parks-to-be-protected-from-fracking-Government-says.html |title=National parks to be 'protected' from fracking, Government says |author=Peter Dominiczak |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014 }}</ref>\u2014seen as a method of reducing anger in Conservative constituencies ahead of the election.<ref name=georgia>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fracking/10995052/Fracking-Matthew-Hancock-fails-to-name-a-single-village-that-supports-it.html#disqus_thread |title=Fracking: Matthew Hancock fails to name a single village that supports it |author=Georgia Graham |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014 }}</ref> Interviewed on the Radio 4 ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme, he rejected the suggestion that fracking was highly unpopular but when challenged was unable to name a single village which supported it.<ref name=\"georgia\"/><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/10/02/tory-minister-retweets-labour-is-full-of-queers-poem/?medium=79120+Tory+Minister+retweets+%E2%80%98Labour+is+full+of+queers%E2%80%99+poem|title=Tory Minister retweets 'Labour is full of queers' poem \u2013 PinkNews \u00b7 PinkNews|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|date=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn his role as Minister of State for Energy, he was criticised for hiring a private jet to fly back from a climate conference<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/apr/02/energy-minister-under-fire-for-hiring-jet-to-fly-back-from-climate-change-deal |work=The Guardian |location= London |author=Severin Carrell |title= Energy minister under fire for hiring jet to fly back from climate change deal |date=2 April 2015}}</ref> and accepting money<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/10/energy-climate-change-minister-matthew-hancock-donations-climate-sceptic |title=Energy and climate change minister accepts \u00a318,000 from climate sceptic |author=Rowena Mason |work=The Guardian |location= London |date=10 April 2015}}</ref> from a key backer of [[climate change denial]] organisation [[Global Warming Policy Foundation]]. In October 2014, he apologised after retweeting a poem suggesting that the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] was \"full of queers\", describing his actions as a \"total accident\".<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29462882 |title=Minister Matthew Hancock sorry for 'queers' retweet |publisher=BBC News |date=2 October 2014 |accessdate=8 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHancock became Minister for the Cabinet Office and [[Paymaster General]] on 11 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/matthew-hancock |title=The Rt Hon Matt Hancock MP |publisher=[[Gov.uk]] }}</ref> He headed [[David Cameron]]'s \"earn or learn\" taskforce which aimed to have every young person earning or learning from April 2017. He announced that jobless 18- to 21-year-olds would be required to do work experience as well as looking for jobs, or face losing their benefits.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hancock-every-young-person-should-be-earning-or-learning-from-april-2017 |title=Hancock: Every young person should be earning or learning from April 2017 |publisher=[[Cabinet Office]] |date=17 August 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 UK referendum on EU membership]], Hancock supported the UK remaining within the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|publisher=BBC News|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHancock moved to the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] as the [[Minister for Culture, Communications and Creative Industries|Minister of State for Digital and Culture]] on 15 July 2016 after [[Theresa May]] became Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-07-16/new-jobs-for-east-anglian-mps-as-ministers-in-may-government/ |title=New jobs for East Anglian MPs as ministers in May government |work=[[ITV News]] |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=17 July 2016 }}</ref> As minister for digital policy, Hancock in June 2017 recommitted to a \"full fibre\" digital policy. This promised that 97% of the UK would enjoy \"superfast broadband\" at speeds of at least 24 megabits per second by 2020.<ref>Mark Jackson, ISP review, \"Digital Minister Matt Hancock Recommits to \"Full Fibre\" Broadband Policy\", 14 June 2017</ref>\n\n===Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport===\nOn 8 January 2018, Hancock was appointed [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]] in Theresa May's [[2018 British cabinet reshuffle|2018 cabinet reshuffle]], succeeding [[Karen Bradley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-politics-42602570|title=Reshuffle: Hancock promoted to cabinet|publisher=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, Hancock was the first MP to launch his own [[smartphone app]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42902684|title='Hi I'm Matt Hancock - here's my app'|date=1 February 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> The head of privacy rights group [[Big Brother Watch]] called the app a \"fascinating comedy of errors\",<ref>{{cite journal|last=Burgess|first=Matt|date=February 2018|title=Matt Hancock MP has launched an app. And he wants all your data|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/matt-hancock-app-dcms-iphone-android-privacy-data|journal=Wired UK|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> after the app was found to collect its users' photographs, friend details, check-ins, and contact information.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/culture-secretary-matt-hancock-mocked-for-launching-social-media-network-11232248|title=Culture Secretary Matt Hancock mocked for launching social media network|work=Sky News|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary of State for Health and Social Care===\nFollowing the appointment of [[Jeremy Hunt]] to the position of [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]], Hancock was appointed to [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]] on Monday 9 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/matthew-hancock|publisher=gov.uk|accessdate=9 November 2019|title=Rt Hon Matt Hancock}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Hancock was criticised after appearing to endorse a mobile phone health app marketed by the subscription health service company [[Babylon Health|Babylon]] in the ''[[Evening Standard]]''. Babylon allegedly sponsored the newspaper article. [[Justin Madders]] wrote to Theresa May accusing Hancock of repeatedly endorsing the products of a company that receives NHS funds for patients it treats, which contravenes ministerial guidelines. The ministerial code includes that ministers should not \"normally accept invitations to act as patrons of, or otherwise offer support to, pressure groups or organisations dependent in whole or in part on government funding\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/30/matt-hancock-accused-of-breaching-code-over-gp-app-endorsement|title=Matt Hancock accused of breaching code over GP app endorsement|author=Rajeev Syal|work=Guardian newspapers|date=30 November 2018|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Hancock, who had previously said the NHS would face \"no privatisation on my watch\", was criticised for allowing 21 NHS contracts worth \u00a3127m to be tendered.<ref name=\"Kentish 2019\">{{cite news | last=Kentish | first=Benjamin | title=NHS offering \u00a3127m of contracts to private companies despite health secretary pledging: 'No privatisation on my watch' | work=The Independent | date=2019-04-06 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nhs-privatisation-health-secretary-contracts-companies-matt-hancock-jon-ashworth-a8857021.html | access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHancock continued in his role as Health Secretary in Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s cabinet. He supported the [[2019 British prorogation controversy|prorogation of parliament in 2019]] by Johnson which he had previously opposed while running for the leadership of the Conservative Party earlier in the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/31/matt-hancock-rows-back-from-views-on-suspending-parliament|title=Matt Hancock rows back from views on suspending parliament|work=The Guardian|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The prorogation was later ruled on 24 September as unlawful by the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261|title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule|work=BBC News|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2019 [[Channel 4 News]] interview, Hancock was asked to respond to allegations Boris Johnson had, at a private lunch in 1999, groped the leg of journalist Charlotte Edwardes under a table. Edwardes also claimed that Johnson did the same to another woman at the same private lunch. In his reply to the Channel 4 News question, Hancock said of Charlotte Edwardes, \"I know Charlotte well and I entirely trust what she has to say. I know her and I know her to be trustworthy\", a view shared by fellow Conservative MP [[Amber Rudd]]. Both Johnson and anonymous Downing Street officials denied the allegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/29/no-10-denies-claims-boris-johnson-squeezed-thigh-journalist-charlotte-edwardes|title=No 10 denies claims Boris Johnson squeezed journalist's thigh|last=Proctor|first=Kate|date=29 September 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 September 2019|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49873301|title=No 10 denies Johnson 'thigh squeeze' claim|last=|first=|date=29 September 2019|work=BBC News online|access-date=29 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/30/sajid-javid-backs-boris-johnson-on-groping-allegations|title=Boris Johnson denies groping allegation after backing from Javid|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 November 2019|date=30 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nHancock drew criticism in November 2019, following the total seclusion of 18-year-old Bethany, an autistic teenager, for almost 3 years in the tiny rooms of psychiatric facilities across [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. The minister publicly apologised \"for the things that have gone wrong in her care\" and claimed her case in particular was \"incredibly difficult and complex\". Bethany's case attracted national attention towards the detention of hundreds of young people living with [[autism]] or other learning disabilities in Britain, and demanded an inquiry into the [[mental health]] system by a parliamentary committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/europe/bethany-autism-matt-hancock.html|title=U.K. Minister Apologizes for Case of Teen With Autism Kept in Seclusion|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] was confirmed to have [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|spread]] to the UK, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Hancock said that the government was considering \"some quite significant actions that would have social and economic disruption\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/matt-hancock-ministers-to-publish-coronavirus-battle-plan-for-uk|title=Matt Hancock: shutting down UK cities 'may become necessary'|work=The Guardian|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=1 March 2020|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> After the government gave strict social distancing advice which was defied by large numbers of people, Hancock took a stronger line than the prime minister on condemning those still socialising in groups and derided them as being \"very selfish\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/23/hancock-socialising-uk-slowing-coronavirus-effort|title=Hancock accuses those still socialising in UK of being 'very selfish'|date=2020-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 27 March, along with Boris Johnson, Hancock himself tested positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"COVID19\">{{cite news|title=Health Secretary Matt Hancock tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-27/health-secretary-matt-hancock-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/|work=ITV News|publisher=ITV|date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==2019 Conservative Party leadership candidacy==\n{{main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\nAfter [[Theresa May]] announced her intention to resign as Prime Minister Hancock announced his intention to stand for the Conservative Party leadership. During this campaign, Hancock opposed the [[Prorogation in the United Kingdom|prorogation of parliament]] to deliver [[Brexit]] and called on his fellow leadership candidates to join him on 6 June 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/29/mad-suggestion-how-tory-ministers-once-viewed-call-to-prorogue-parliament|title='Mad suggestion': how Tory ministers once viewed call to prorogue parliament|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 August 2019|date=29 August 2019|last=Rourke|first=Alison}}</ref> He proposed a televised debate with other candidates.<ref name=\"candidate\">{{cite news |title=Hunt warns against no-deal Brexit 'suicide' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48428761 |accessdate=28 May 2019 |agency=BBC News |date=28 May 2019}}</ref> He withdrew from the race on 14 June shortly after winning only twenty votes on the first ballot.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tory leadership: Matt Hancock quits contest|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48631706 |accessdate=14 June 2019 |agency=BBC News |date=14 June 2019}}</ref> Following his withdrawal, he endorsed Boris Johnson for the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/matt-hancock-boris-and-i-have-had-our-differences-but-he-s-the-one-to-unite-us-mzhqrbvnd|title=Matt Hancock: Boris and I have had our differences but he's the one to unite us|first=Matt|last=Hancock|date=16 June 2019|publisher=|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHancock married Martha Hoyer Millar, an [[osteopath]], in 2006.<ref name=UKWW/> She is a granddaughter of [[Frederick Millar, 1st Baron Inchyra]].<ref>{{cite news|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 October 2005|title=Hancock/Hoyer Millar engagement}}</ref> They have a daughter and two sons.<ref name=\"FTYoungMinister\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/06/11/take-mobile-phones-children-night-says-minister/|title=Culture Secretary Matt Hancock reveals he does not allow his children to use social media|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=11 June 2018|last=Mikhailova|first=Anna}}</ref> They live in [[Little Thurlow]] in his West Suffolk parliamentary constituency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cheshire-live.co.uk/news/chester-cheshire-news/new-health-secretary-chester-born-14888785|title=New health secretary is Chester-born Matt Hancock MP|work=Cheshire Live|date=10 July 2018}}</ref> Hancock has an older sister and a brother.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/08/sister-government-minister-suffers-traumatic-brain-injury-falling/|title=Sister of government minister suffers 'traumatic brain injury' after falling from horse |work=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 May 2017|last=Sabur|first=Rozina}}</ref> He reports having [[dyslexia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/oct/03/matt-hancock-dyslexia-struggles-strengthen-case-against-send-cuts|work=The Guardian|title=Matt Hancock dyslexia struggles 'strengthen case against cuts'|date=3 October 2018|last=Weaver|first=Matthew}}</ref>\nHe also supports Newcastle United, and was presented a signed shirt of the 2019/20 season which he keeps in his private office.\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = matthew-hancock/4070 | publicwhip = matthew_hancock | theywork = matthew_hancock}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richard Spring, Baron Risby|Richard Spring]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]]|years=2010\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Hayes (British politician)|John Hayes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Skills and Enterprise]]|years=2013\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Boles]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=3|before=[[Michael Fallon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Business and Enterprise]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anna Soubry]]|as=Minister of State for Small Business}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrea Leadsom]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Portsmouth|Minister of State for Portsmouth]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mark Francois]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Francis Maude]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for the Cabinet Office]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Ben Gummer]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Paymaster General]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ed Vaizey]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of State for Digital and Culture]]|years=2016\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Margot James]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Karen Bradley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]]|years=2018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jeremy Wright]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Hunt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cabinet of David Cameron}}\n{{First Cameron Cabinet}}\n{{Second Cameron Cabinet}}\n{{Second May Cabinet}}\n{{Johnson Cabinet}}\n{{Department for Culture, Media and Sport}}\n{{Secretary of State for Culture}}\n{{Secretary of State for Health}}\n{{2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\n{{East of England Conservative Party MPs}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hancock, Matthew}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Bank of England]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Chester]]\n[[Category:People from Chester]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of State for Health and Social Care]]\n[[Category:British Secretaries of State]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the British politician|the character from the soap opera ''Neighbours''|Matt Hancock (Neighbours)}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = Matt Hancock\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of Rt Hon Matt Hancock MP crop 2.jpg\n| office1 = [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Theresa May]]<br />[[Boris Johnson]]\n| term_start1 = 9 July 2018\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Jeremy Hunt]]\n| successor1 = \n| office2 = [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start2 = 8 January 2018\n| term_end2 = 9 July 2018\n| predecessor2 = [[Karen Bradley]]\n| successor2 = [[Jeremy Wright]]\n| office3 = [[Minister for Culture, Communications and Creative Industries|Minister of State for Digital and Culture]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start3 = 15 July 2016\n| term_end3 = 8 January 2018\n| predecessor3 = [[Ed Vaizey]]\n| successor3 = [[Margot James]]\n| office4 = [[Minister for the Cabinet Office]]<br />[[Paymaster General]]\n| primeminister4 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start4 = 11 May 2015\n| term_end4 = 14 July 2016\n| predecessor4 = [[Francis Maude]]\n| successor4 = [[Ben Gummer]]\n| office5 = [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Business and Enterprise]]\n| primeminister5 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start5 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end5 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor5 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor5 = [[Anna Soubry]]\n| office6 = [[Minister of State at the Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]\n| primeminister6 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start6 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end6 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor6 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor6 = [[Andrea Leadsom]]\n| office7 = [[Minister for Portsmouth|Minister of State for Portsmouth]]\n| primeminister7 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start7 = 15 July 2014\n| term_end7 = 11 May 2015\n| predecessor7 = [[Michael Fallon]]\n| successor7 = [[Mark Francois]]\n| office8 = [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Skills and Enterprise]]\n| primeminister8 = [[David Cameron]]\n| term_start8 = 8 September 2013\n| term_end8 = 15 July 2014\n| predecessor8 = [[John Hayes (British politician)|John Hayes]]\n| successor8 = [[Nick Boles]]\n| office9 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]]\n| term_start9 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end9 = \n| predecessor9 = [[Richard Spring, Baron Risby|Richard Spring]]\n| successor9 = \n| majority9 = 23,194 (45.1%)\n| birth_name = Matthew John David Hancock\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1978|10|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Chester]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| education = [[The King's School, Chester]]\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of Oxford]]\n* [[University of Cambridge]]\n}}\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = {{married|Martha Hoyer Millar|2006}}\n| children = 3\n| website = {{URL|www.matt-hancock.com}}\n| caption = Hancock in 2020\n}}\n'''Matthew John David Hancock''' (born 2 October 1978) is a senior British politician serving as [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]], since 2018. A member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], he has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]] since [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]].\n\nHancock was born in [[Cheshire]], where his family runs a software business. Hancock studied for a BA in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]] (PPE) at [[Exeter College, Oxford]], and an MPhil in Economics at [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], as a postgraduate student. He was an economist at the Bank of England before serving as a senior economic advisor (and later Chief of Staff) to [[George Osborne]].\n\nHancock served in a number of middle-ranking ministerial positions from September 2013 under both [[David Cameron]] and [[Theresa May]]. He was promoted to the Cabinet in the [[2018 British cabinet reshuffle|January 2018 cabinet reshuffle]] when he was appointed [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-42602570|title=Cabinet reshuffle: Greening quits government|publisher=BBC News|date=8 January 2018|accessdate=8 January 2018}}</ref> On 9 July 2018, after the promotion of [[Jeremy Hunt]] to Foreign Secretary, Hancock was named [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/matt-hancock-health-secretary-jeremy-hunt-app-theresa-may-foreign-secretary-boris-johnson-a8439506.html|title=Matt Hancock replaces Jeremy Hunt as health secretary|work=The Independent|access-date=2018-07-09|language=en-GB}}</ref> On 25 May 2019, Hancock announced his intention to stand in the [[2019 Conservative Party leadership election]]. He withdrew from the race on 14 June shortly after the first ballot.         \n\n==Early life and career==\nMatthew John David Hancock was born on 2 October 1978 in [[Chester]], [[Cheshire]], to Michael Hancock and Shirley Hills (now Carter).<ref name=UKWW>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-251113|title=Hancock, Rt Hon. Matthew (John David)|publisher=UK Who's Who|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\nHancock attended Farndon County Primary School, in [[Farndon, Cheshire|Farndon]], Cheshire, and the [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|independent]] [[King's School, Chester|King's School]], Chester. He later studied computing at the further education college, [[West Cheshire College]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://feweek.co.uk/2014/04/24/with-two-offices-across-two-government-departments-two-secretaries-of-state-as-bosses-and-one-of-the-broadest-ministerial-briefs-around-life-is-hectic-for-matthew-hancock/|publisher=FE Week|date=24 April 2014|accessdate=18 October 2019|title=Matthew Hancock MP, skills minister|last=Whittaker|first=Freddie}}</ref><ref name=King>{{cite web|url=https://www.kingschester.co.uk/news/alumni-news/cabinet-role-mp-matt-hancock/|title=Cabinet role for MP Matt Hancock|publisher=King's School Chester|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref> He studied at [[Exeter College, Oxford]], and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#First class honours|first]] in [[Philosophy, Politics and Economics]], and went on to [[Christ's College, Cambridge]], to earn an [[Master of Philosophy|MPhil]] degree in Economics.<ref name=King/><ref name=\"FTYoungMinister\">{{cite news |title=Young minister has the skills to climb to the top in Westminster |url=https://www.ft.com/content/027bd85e-0290-11e4-a68d-00144feab7de |accessdate=10 July 2018 |work=Financial Times}}</ref> Hancock became a member of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/matthew-hancock/84378|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120808232448/http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/matthew-hancock/84378|archivedate=2012-08-08|title=Matthew Hancock|website=www.parliament.uk |date=8 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAfter university, Hancock briefly worked for his family's [[computer software]] company, before moving to London to work as an economist at the [[Bank of England]], specialising in the [[housing market]]. In 2005, he became an economic adviser to the [[Shadow Chancellor of the Exchequer]] [[George Osborne]], later becoming Osborne's chief of staff.<ref name=\"FTYoungMinister\"/><ref name=\"Times\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/voters-don-t-want-extremes-they-want-the-centre-cn9lbhqnz|title=Matt Hancock interview: 'Voters want the centre, not the extremes'|date=4 May 2019|last1=Thomson|first1=Alice|last2=Sylvester|first2=Rachel|work=The Times|accessdate=18 October 2019}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n\nHancock was selected as the Conservative candidate for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]] in January 2010. He narrowly won the contest, defeating [[Natalie Elphicke]] (solicitor and wife of politician [[Charlie Elphicke]]), by 88 votes to 81 in the final ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.conservativehome.com/highlights/2018/05/profile-matt-hancock-the-osborne-acolyte-who-managed-to-survive-and-prosper.html|publisher=Conservative Home|title=Profile: Matt Hancock, the Osborne acolyte who managed to survive and prosper|last=Gimson|first=Andrew|date=10 May 2018|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nHancock was elected as the Member of Parliament for West Suffolk at the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] with 24,312 votes, 13,050 votes ahead of [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] candidate Belinda Brooks-Gordon.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/constituency/f10.stm |title=Election 2010: Constituency: Suffolk West |work=[[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> In June, Hancock was elected to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]], the [[Select committee (United Kingdom)|select committee]] responsible for overseeing government expenditures to ensure they are effective and honest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conservativehome.blogs.com/parliament/2010/06/members-of-the-2010-intake-dominate-the-conservative-membership-of-select-committees.html |title=Members of the 2010 intake dominate the Conservative membership of Select Committees Tory MPs |work=[[Conservative Home]] |date=24 June 2010 |accessdate=8 April 2015 |archivedate=27 June 2010 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100627030054/http://conservativehome.blogs.com/parliament/2010/06/members-of-the-2010-intake-dominate-the-conservative-membership-of-select-committees.html }}</ref> He served on this committee until November 2012. Hancock has also served on the [[Standards and Privileges Committee]] between October 2010 and December 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/matt-hancock/4070|title=Rt Hon Matt Hancock|accessdate=9 November 2019|publisher=parliament.uk}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, he was accused of dishonesty by ''[[Daybreak (2010 TV programme)|Daybreak]]'' presenter [[Matt Barbet]] after claiming he had been excluded from a discussion about apprentices after turning up \"just 30 seconds late\".<ref name=\"HHH\">{{cite news |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9795367/Hancocks-half-hour-Tory-minister-accused-of-dishonesty-about-missed-TV-appearance.html |title=Hancock's half-hour: Tory minister accused of 'dishonesty' about missed TV appearance |author=Peter Dominiczak |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=11 January 2013 |accessdate=11 January 2013 }}</ref> Barbet said Hancock knew he was \"much more than a minute late\" and he should have arrived half an hour beforehand to prepare for the interview. An activist who was due to appear with Hancock expressed surprise that \"a minister whose Government berates 'shirkers' couldn't be bothered to get out of bed to defend his own policy\".<ref name=\"HHH\"/>\n\n===Junior ministerial roles===\nIn October 2013, Hancock joined the [[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills]] as the Minister of State for Skills & Enterprise.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityam.com/cabinet-reshuffle-who-matt-hancock-meet-david-cameron-s-new-minister-business-enterprise/|publisher=City A.M.|accessdate=9 November 2019|date=15 July 2014|title=Who is Matt Hancock? Meet David Cameron's new business minister}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 July 2014, Hancock was appointed to the position of Minister of State for Business and Enterprise.  He also took on additional responsibilities as the Minister of State for Portsmouth. On 27 July he announced protection from [[fracking]] for [[National parks of England and Wales|National Parks]]<ref name=\"pete\">{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fracking/10994412/National-parks-to-be-protected-from-fracking-Government-says.html |title=National parks to be 'protected' from fracking, Government says |author=Peter Dominiczak |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014 }}</ref>\u2014seen as a method of reducing anger in Conservative constituencies ahead of the election.<ref name=georgia>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/earth/energy/fracking/10995052/Fracking-Matthew-Hancock-fails-to-name-a-single-village-that-supports-it.html#disqus_thread |title=Fracking: Matthew Hancock fails to name a single village that supports it |author=Georgia Graham |work=The Daily Telegraph |location= London |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014 }}</ref> Interviewed on the Radio 4 ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme, he rejected the suggestion that fracking was highly unpopular but when challenged was unable to name a single village which supported it.<ref name=\"georgia\"/><ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2014/10/02/tory-minister-retweets-labour-is-full-of-queers-poem/?medium=79120+Tory+Minister+retweets+%E2%80%98Labour+is+full+of+queers%E2%80%99+poem|title=Tory Minister retweets 'Labour is full of queers' poem \u2013 PinkNews \u00b7 PinkNews|website=www.pinknews.co.uk|date=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn his role as Minister of State for Energy, he was criticised for hiring a private jet to fly back from a climate conference<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/apr/02/energy-minister-under-fire-for-hiring-jet-to-fly-back-from-climate-change-deal |work=The Guardian |location= London |author=Severin Carrell |title= Energy minister under fire for hiring jet to fly back from climate change deal |date=2 April 2015}}</ref> and accepting money<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/apr/10/energy-climate-change-minister-matthew-hancock-donations-climate-sceptic |title=Energy and climate change minister accepts \u00a318,000 from climate sceptic |author=Rowena Mason |work=The Guardian |location= London |date=10 April 2015}}</ref> from a key backer of [[climate change denial]] organisation [[Global Warming Policy Foundation]]. In October 2014, he apologised after retweeting a poem suggesting that the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] was \"full of queers\", describing his actions as a \"total accident\".<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29462882 |title=Minister Matthew Hancock sorry for 'queers' retweet |publisher=BBC News |date=2 October 2014 |accessdate=8 April 2015 }}</ref>\n\nHancock became Minister for the Cabinet Office and [[Paymaster General]] on 11 May 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/matthew-hancock |title=The Rt Hon Matt Hancock MP |publisher=[[Gov.uk]] }}</ref> He headed [[David Cameron]]'s \"earn or learn\" taskforce which aimed to have every young person earning or learning from April 2017. He announced that jobless 18- to 21-year-olds would be required to do work experience as well as looking for jobs, or face losing their benefits.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/hancock-every-young-person-should-be-earning-or-learning-from-april-2017 |title=Hancock: Every young person should be earning or learning from April 2017 |publisher=[[Cabinet Office]] |date=17 August 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 UK referendum on EU membership]], Hancock supported the UK remaining within the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|publisher=BBC News|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=18 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nHancock moved to the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] as the [[Minister for Culture, Communications and Creative Industries|Minister of State for Digital and Culture]] on 15 July 2016 after [[Theresa May]] became Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.itv.com/news/anglia/2016-07-16/new-jobs-for-east-anglian-mps-as-ministers-in-may-government/ |title=New jobs for East Anglian MPs as ministers in May government |work=[[ITV News]] |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=17 July 2016 }}</ref> As minister for digital policy, Hancock in June 2017 recommitted to a \"full fibre\" digital policy. This promised that 97% of the UK would enjoy \"superfast broadband\" at speeds of at least 24 megabits per second by 2020.<ref>Mark Jackson, ISP review, \"Digital Minister Matt Hancock Recommits to \"Full Fibre\" Broadband Policy\", 14 June 2017</ref>\n\n===Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport===\nOn 8 January 2018, Hancock was appointed [[Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport]] in Theresa May's [[2018 British cabinet reshuffle|2018 cabinet reshuffle]], succeeding [[Karen Bradley]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-politics-42602570|title=Reshuffle: Hancock promoted to cabinet|publisher=BBC News|access-date=2018-01-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2018, Hancock was the first MP to launch his own [[smartphone app]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-42902684|title='Hi I'm Matt Hancock - here's my app'|date=1 February 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> The head of privacy rights group [[Big Brother Watch]] called the app a \"fascinating comedy of errors\",<ref>{{cite journal|last=Burgess|first=Matt|date=February 2018|title=Matt Hancock MP has launched an app. And he wants all your data|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/matt-hancock-app-dcms-iphone-android-privacy-data|journal=Wired UK|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref> after the app was found to collect its users' photographs, friend details, check-ins, and contact information.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/culture-secretary-matt-hancock-mocked-for-launching-social-media-network-11232248|title=Culture Secretary Matt Hancock mocked for launching social media network|work=Sky News|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Secretary of State for Health and Social Care===\nFollowing the appointment of [[Jeremy Hunt]] to the position of [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs]], Hancock was appointed to [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care]] on Monday 9 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/matthew-hancock|publisher=gov.uk|accessdate=9 November 2019|title=Rt Hon Matt Hancock}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Hancock was criticised after appearing to endorse a mobile phone health app marketed by the subscription health service company [[Babylon Health|Babylon]] in the ''[[Evening Standard]]''. Babylon allegedly sponsored the newspaper article. [[Justin Madders]] wrote to Theresa May accusing Hancock of repeatedly endorsing the products of a company that receives NHS funds for patients it treats, which contravenes ministerial guidelines. The ministerial code includes that ministers should not \"normally accept invitations to act as patrons of, or otherwise offer support to, pressure groups or organisations dependent in whole or in part on government funding\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/nov/30/matt-hancock-accused-of-breaching-code-over-gp-app-endorsement|title=Matt Hancock accused of breaching code over GP app endorsement|author=Rajeev Syal|work=Guardian newspapers|date=30 November 2018|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, Hancock, who had previously said the NHS would face \"no privatisation on my watch\", was criticised for allowing 21 NHS contracts worth \u00a3127m to be tendered.<ref name=\"Kentish 2019\">{{cite news | last=Kentish | first=Benjamin | title=NHS offering \u00a3127m of contracts to private companies despite health secretary pledging: 'No privatisation on my watch' | work=The Independent | date=2019-04-06 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/nhs-privatisation-health-secretary-contracts-companies-matt-hancock-jon-ashworth-a8857021.html | access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHancock continued in his role as Health Secretary in Prime Minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s cabinet. He supported the [[2019 British prorogation controversy|prorogation of parliament in 2019]] by Johnson which he had previously opposed while running for the leadership of the Conservative Party earlier in the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/31/matt-hancock-rows-back-from-views-on-suspending-parliament|title=Matt Hancock rows back from views on suspending parliament|work=The Guardian|date=31 August 2019|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The prorogation was later ruled on 24 September as unlawful by the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-49810261|title=Supreme Court: Suspending Parliament was unlawful, judges rule|work=BBC News|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn a September 2019 [[Channel 4 News]] interview, Hancock was asked to respond to allegations Boris Johnson had, at a private lunch in 1999, groped the leg of journalist Charlotte Edwardes under a table. Edwardes also claimed that Johnson did the same to another woman at the same private lunch. In his reply to the Channel 4 News question, Hancock said of Charlotte Edwardes, \"I know Charlotte well and I entirely trust what she has to say. I know her and I know her to be trustworthy\", a view shared by fellow Conservative MP [[Amber Rudd]]. Both Johnson and anonymous Downing Street officials denied the allegation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/29/no-10-denies-claims-boris-johnson-squeezed-thigh-journalist-charlotte-edwardes|title=No 10 denies claims Boris Johnson squeezed journalist's thigh|last=Proctor|first=Kate|date=29 September 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 September 2019|last2=Stewart|first2=Heather|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-49873301|title=No 10 denies Johnson 'thigh squeeze' claim|last=|first=|date=29 September 2019|work=BBC News online|access-date=29 September 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/sep/30/sajid-javid-backs-boris-johnson-on-groping-allegations|title=Boris Johnson denies groping allegation after backing from Javid|work=The Guardian|accessdate=9 November 2019|date=30 September 2019}}</ref> \n\nHancock drew criticism in November 2019, following the total seclusion of 18-year-old Bethany, an autistic teenager, for almost 3 years in the tiny rooms of psychiatric facilities across [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. The minister publicly apologised \"for the things that have gone wrong in her care\" and claimed her case in particular was \"incredibly difficult and complex\". Bethany's case attracted national attention towards the detention of hundreds of young people living with [[autism]] or other learning disabilities in Britain, and demanded an inquiry into the [[mental health]] system by a parliamentary committee.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/10/world/europe/bethany-autism-matt-hancock.html|title=U.K. Minister Apologizes for Case of Teen With Autism Kept in Seclusion|accessdate=10 November 2019|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January 2020, [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] was confirmed to have [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|spread]] to the UK, during the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]. Hancock said that the government was considering \"some quite significant actions that would have social and economic disruption\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/01/matt-hancock-ministers-to-publish-coronavirus-battle-plan-for-uk|title=Matt Hancock: shutting down UK cities 'may become necessary'|work=The Guardian|last=Syal|first=Rajeev|date=1 March 2020|access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref> After the government gave strict social distancing advice which was defied by large numbers of people, Hancock took a stronger line than the prime minister on condemning those still socialising in groups and derided them as being \"very selfish\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mason|first=Rowena|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2020/mar/23/hancock-socialising-uk-slowing-coronavirus-effort|title=Hancock accuses those still socialising in UK of being 'very selfish'|date=2020-03-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> On 27 March, along with Boris Johnson, Hancock himself tested positive for COVID-19.<ref name=\"COVID19\">{{cite news|title=Health Secretary Matt Hancock tests positive for coronavirus|url=https://www.itv.com/news/2020-03-27/health-secretary-matt-hancock-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/|work=ITV News|publisher=ITV|date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==2019 Conservative Party leadership candidacy==\n{{main|2019 Conservative Party leadership election}}\nAfter [[Theresa May]] announced her intention to resign as Prime Minister Hancock announced his intention to stand for the Conservative Party leadership. During this campaign, Hancock opposed the [[Prorogation in the United Kingdom|prorogation of parliament]] to deliver [[Brexit]] and called on his fellow leadership candidates to join him on 6 June 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/aug/29/mad-suggestion-how-tory-ministers-once-viewed-call-to-prorogue-parliament|title='Mad suggestion': how Tory ministers once viewed call to prorogue parliament|work=The Guardian|accessdate=29 August 2019|date=29 August 2019|last=Rourke|first=Alison}}</ref> He proposed a televised debate with other candidates.<ref name=\"candidate\">{{cite news |title=Hunt warns against no-deal Brexit 'suicide' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48428761 |accessdate=28 May 2019 |agency=BBC News |date=28 May 2019}}</ref> He withdrew from the race on 14 June shortly after winning only twenty votes on the first ballot.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tory leadership: Matt Hancock quits contest|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-48631706 |accessdate=14 June 2019 |agency=BBC News |date=14 June 2019}}</ref> Following his withdrawal, he endorsed Boris Johnson for the role.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/matt-hancock-boris-and-i-have-had-our-differences-but-he-s-the-one-to-unite-us-mzhqrbvnd|title=Matt Hancock: Boris and I have had our differences but he's the one to unite us|first=Matt|last=Hancock|date=16 June 2019|publisher=|via=www.thetimes.co.uk|accessdate=17 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHancock married Martha Hoyer Millar, an [[osteopath]], in 2006.<ref name=UKWW/> She is a granddaughter of [[Frederick Millar, 1st Baron Inchyra]].<ref>{{cite news|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 October 2005|title=Hancock/Hoyer Millar engagement}}</ref> They have a daughter and two sons.<ref name=\"FTYoungMinister\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/politics/2018/06/11/take-mobile-phones-children-night-says-minister/|title=Culture Secretary Matt Hancock reveals he does not allow his children to use social media|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=11 June 2018|last=Mikhailova|first=Anna}}</ref> They live in [[Little Thurlow]] in his West Suffolk parliamentary constituency.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cheshire-live.co.uk/news/chester-cheshire-news/new-health-secretary-chester-born-14888785|title=New health secretary is Chester-born Matt Hancock MP|work=Cheshire Live|date=10 July 2018}}</ref> Hancock has an older sister and a brother.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/05/08/sister-government-minister-suffers-traumatic-brain-injury-falling/|title=Sister of government minister suffers 'traumatic brain injury' after falling from horse |work=The Daily Telegraph|date=8 May 2017|last=Sabur|first=Rozina}}</ref> He reports having [[dyslexia]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2018/oct/03/matt-hancock-dyslexia-struggles-strengthen-case-against-send-cuts|work=The Guardian|title=Matt Hancock dyslexia struggles 'strengthen case against cuts'|date=3 October 2018|last=Weaver|first=Matthew}}</ref>\nHe also supports Newcastle United, and was presented a signed shirt of the 2019/20 season which he keeps in his private office.\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{UK MP links | parliament = matthew-hancock/4070 | publicwhip = matthew_hancock | theywork = matthew_hancock}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Richard Spring, Baron Risby|Richard Spring]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br />for [[West Suffolk (UK Parliament constituency)|West Suffolk]]|years=2010\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Hayes (British politician)|John Hayes]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Skills and Enterprise]]|years=2013\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Nick Boles]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=3|before=[[Michael Fallon]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department for Business, Innovation and Skills|Minister of State for Business and Enterprise]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Anna Soubry]]|as=Minister of State for Small Business}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Department of Energy and Climate Change|Minister of State for Energy]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrea Leadsom]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister for Portsmouth|Minister of State for Portsmouth]]|years=2014\u20132015}}\n{{s